[start section id="20112"]

#1 Adenocarcinoma of the colon
There are two masses that have been biopsy-proven as adenocarcinoma from the outside hospital.  The first of these is in the midascending colon and the second at the 15-cm mark, biopsy-proven from the outside hospital as adenocarcinoma.  Biopsy slides are being sent to GCGH as we speak, and we have discussed the possible options of management of these chronic masses.  The concern is this lesion near the rectum and we are evaluating this further with a rectal endoscopic ultrasound in addition to a pelvic MRI with a rectal coil in case that this is invading the rectum then preoperative radiotherapy may need to be considered.  A PET CT has also been arranged for further evaluation of the extent of disease.
#2 Numerous colonic polyps
This is suggestive of FAP, and outside biopsies have returned as tubular and tubulovillous adenomas.  We have requested an extended EGD with side view for evaluation of any duodenal polyps prior to his surgery to address the best surgical option of this.  Mr. Ortiz has been scheduled to see Medical Genetics.
#3 Preoperative evaluation
Mr. Ortiz is being scheduled for an ECG, chest x-ray, and lab work.  His performance status is 1, and he has no significant comorbidities.  We have emphasized the importance of him remaining off any tobacco substances.  If his preoperative evaluations return as normal, then he is okay for surgery.
This case was discussed and supervised by Dr. Calderon and Carolyn Ruhl our nurse practitioner who was present in the subsequent consultation.
ADVANCE DIRECTIVES
Advance directive or living will: No, not interested in additional information.

[end section id="20112"]

