Evaluation of recently-diagnosed adenocarcinoma of the bowel and numerous polyps within the colon.

[end section id="20102"]

[start section id="20103"]

Mr. Ortiz is a very pleasant 42-year-old gentleman from KY North Carolina, who was seen in the Gastroenterology Clinic accompanied by his wife.  He comes here for further evaluation and treatment for recently-diagnosed adenocarcinoma in his bowel with numerous polyps within his large bowel also seen.
From a symptom standpoint, Mr. Ortiz states that for the last year he has been having intermittent discomfort below his right rib.  Two-to-three months ago, while playing baseball with his child, he noticed more discomfort in this area and in the last week of May this discomfort became persistent and associated with a slight fever.  He continues to have one bowel movement a day on a daily basis, but over the last six-months he has noticed this becoming a little looser but has not noticed any blood per rectum.  He gets occasional constipation with the last episode six-months ago where during these episodes he developed symptoms consistent with hemorrhoids and bright-red blood on the tissue paper.  His weight has, otherwise, been stable, and he has had no change in appetite, no symptoms of nausea or vomiting, and no dysphagia.
He went to his local physician on the 5th of July for evaluation of this persistent right upper quadrant pain, and a CT-scan demonstrated a 7.7-cm x 5-cm x 5.6-cm mass in the cecum.  He had a subsequent colonoscopy performed at an outside hospital on the 13th of July which showed a large obstructing, ulcerating, partly necrotic mass in the midascending colon just distal to the cecum.  Also, an ulcerated infiltrating mass was seen at the 15-cm mark and innumerable 1- to 3-mm polyps were seen within the colon.  Biopsies of these two masses returned back as adenocarcinoma, and the biopsies of the polyps that were removed were tubular or tubulovillous adenomas.  Mr. Ortiz informs me that the actual biopsy slides are on their way to GCGH and should arrive here today.
Mr. Ortiz's local care providers were planning for him to have surgery, and Mr. Ortiz and his wife thought that it would be prudent to have a further evaluation performed here.

[end section id="20103"]

